and part two, Robert will be talking about level lighting.

35
00:01:21,542 --> 00:01:21,842
Let's go.

36
00:01:22,823 --> 00:01:24,864
First up, let's get all on the same page.

37
00:01:25,745 --> 00:01:26,986
What the heck is block mesh?

38
00:01:28,627 --> 00:01:30,528
Well, at Naughty Dog, we call levels built

39
00:01:30,548 --> 00:01:32,430
with simple geometry and textures block mesh.

40
00:01:32,990 --> 00:01:34,711
Unfortunately, our industry hasn't arrived

41
00:01:34,751 --> 00:01:35,832
at a single term at this yet.

42
00:01:36,742 --> 00:01:38,623
They also call it gray box and white box

43
00:01:38,683 --> 00:01:39,483
and all kinds of things.

44
00:01:40,263 --> 00:01:41,923
Mostly, I prefer block mesh because it

45
00:01:41,943 --> 00:01:43,704
includes color and lighting, which

46
00:01:43,724 --> 00:01:45,604
are very important when playtesting layouts,

47
00:01:45,984 --> 00:01:47,144
since they help guide players.

48
00:01:48,085 --> 00:01:50,625
Also, handing off colored block meshes to your artists

49
00:01:50,805 --> 00:01:52,125
make it a lot easier to communicate

50
00:01:52,145 --> 00:01:54,846
the kinds of textures and colors you had in mind.

51
00:01:55,506 --> 00:01:57,007
Green floor, it's probably grass.

52
00:01:57,267 --> 00:01:58,307
Brown, it's probably dirt.

53
00:01:59,827 --> 00:02:02,748
Now let's look at a common level design process at a game

54
00:02:02,788 --> 00:02:03,088
studio.

55
00:02:03,862 --> 00:02:06,023
First, you need to establish the context and constraints

56
00:02:06,043 --> 00:02:06,503
of your level.

57
00:02:07,404 --> 00:02:09,085
This includes things like the environment type,

58
00:02:09,365 --> 00:02:11,266
the time of day, location in the story,

59
00:02:11,466 --> 00:02:14,067
available character abilities, enemy types, all that stuff.

60
00:02:14,887 --> 00:02:16,868
You should decide on the game plan narrative beats, too.

61
00:02:18,209 --> 00:02:19,570
Once you have your requirements and beats,

62
00:02:20,010 --> 00:02:22,951
dive right into building a rough version of the entire level

63
00:02:23,271 --> 00:02:25,372
so that you can get a sense of pacing and scale.

64
00:02:26,133 --> 00:02:28,214
Be sure to stub in those game plan narrative beats, too.

65
00:02:29,574 --> 00:02:31,675
Get something playable quickly, and then watch other people

66
00:02:31,715 --> 00:02:31,975
play it.

67
00:02:32,416 --> 00:02:34,097
There's no need for a formal play test or anything.

68
00:02:34,117 --> 00:02:36,899
You can just grab anybody, because the feedback

69
00:02:36,919 --> 00:02:38,760
that you get from them is going to change a block mesh.

70
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:42,682
Repeat this iteration loop until you basically run out of time.

71
00:02:43,642 --> 00:02:45,643
And once you run out of time, your layout's locked,

72
00:02:45,784 --> 00:02:47,084
and you hand it off to the rest of the team

73
00:02:47,104 --> 00:02:48,005
to make it look amazing.

74
00:02:48,585 --> 00:02:49,686
But your job isn't done yet.

75
00:02:50,126 --> 00:02:51,887
Your task at this stage is to ensure

76
00:02:51,907 --> 00:02:54,228
that your design goals mesh with their artistic goals.

77
00:02:54,789 --> 00:02:56,890
So keep play testing, and work with your artists

78
00:02:56,930 --> 00:02:59,111
to ensure that it still plays great with the real art.

79
00:02:59,932 --> 00:03:01,192
Now, it's worth noting that every studio

80
00:03:01,212 --> 00:03:02,013
has a different process.

81
00:03:02,518 --> 00:03:04,519
but this core iteration loop is universal.

82
00:03:05,699 --> 00:03:07,100
So now let's get to the block mesh tips.

83
00:03:07,700 --> 00:03:09,521
Now, our game director Kurt told me

84
00:03:09,561 --> 00:03:11,763
that tips wasn't a strong enough word for how important

85
00:03:11,783 --> 00:03:13,663
these are, so I'm going to rename them now

86
00:03:13,723 --> 00:03:15,164
to guidance principles.

87
00:03:16,705 --> 00:03:18,466
So first up, we have affordance.

88
00:03:20,167 --> 00:03:21,968
One of the most powerful ways to guide players

89
00:03:22,068 --> 00:03:24,549
is by using affordances, which are properties of an object

90
00:03:24,829 --> 00:03:27,310
that define its possible uses and make clear

91
00:03:27,350 --> 00:03:28,131
how it should be used.

92
00:03:29,231 --> 00:03:30,812
A classic example is a door handle.

93
00:03:31,498 --> 00:03:33,439
Just by looking at a push bar or a pull handle,

94
00:03:33,739 --> 00:03:35,700
you intuit whether or not to push or pull the door

95
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:36,420
as you approach.

96
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:38,580
Ladders afford climbing.

97
00:03:40,161 --> 00:03:41,361
Edges also afford climbing.

98
00:03:42,921 --> 00:03:45,902
Ramps afford jumping off or smashing through a vent

99
00:03:45,982 --> 00:03:46,822
in Wolfenstein II.

100
00:03:47,643 --> 00:03:49,143
Affordances depend on your game rules

101
00:03:49,163 --> 00:03:50,963
because that's what they're communicating to the player.

102
00:03:52,184 --> 00:03:54,384
So for our game designers, affordance

103
00:03:54,424 --> 00:03:57,465
is a great way to communicate to the player what they can interact

104
00:03:57,505 --> 00:03:58,545
with or where they can go.

105
00:03:59,308 --> 00:04:00,749
Players will learn what is interactive,

106
00:04:00,929 --> 00:04:02,770
and it will attract them towards these affordances.

107
00:04:04,051 --> 00:04:06,553
Consistent color and shape establish a trust contract

108
00:04:06,853 --> 00:04:09,454
with players who use these to learn your game rules.

109
00:04:10,875 --> 00:04:12,416
You should ensure that all of your affordances

110
00:04:12,456 --> 00:04:13,837
work consistently throughout the game,

111
00:04:13,977 --> 00:04:15,738
or it breaks that trust contract, which

112
00:04:15,778 --> 00:04:16,978
will cause player frustration.

113
00:04:18,559 --> 00:04:20,180
You should also include affordances

114
00:04:20,360 --> 00:04:21,361
in your block mesh phase.

115
00:04:21,861 --> 00:04:23,482
It'll help guide players where you want them to go.

116
00:04:23,502 --> 00:04:24,823
So let's see what it looks like.

117
00:04:27,524 --> 00:04:30,486
So in this block mesh, it's not clear where the player should go next.

118
00:04:31,067 --> 00:04:33,710
Sure, the ladder affords climbing up the little tower, but then what?

119
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:35,531
Jump to the cliff, dive in the water?

120
00:04:36,072 --> 00:04:39,275
But if we add some affordances, it becomes clear where to go.

121
00:04:39,976 --> 00:04:42,098
The boards on the roof afford jumping to the cliff,

122
00:04:43,719 --> 00:04:45,661
while the edge grabs on the cliffs afford climbing.

123
00:04:46,242 --> 00:04:48,644
Of course, this example is tailor-made for Uncharted,

124
00:04:49,165 --> 00:04:52,268
but the game's same concepts will apply to your traversal mechanics.

125
00:04:53,072 --> 00:04:54,894
It may seem silly to add them so early,

126
00:04:55,194 --> 00:04:57,075
but trust me, it makes a world of difference

127
00:04:57,175 --> 00:04:58,396
in how your playtests go,

128
00:04:58,616 --> 00:04:59,857
and it doesn't take that much effort.

129
00:05:01,058 --> 00:05:01,619
And one more thing.

130
00:05:02,019 --> 00:05:05,662
Ensure these affordances use consistent shape and color.

131
00:05:06,222 --> 00:05:07,183
Follow the game metrics,

132
00:05:07,303 --> 00:05:09,565
and you empower your team with this information.

133
00:05:10,205 --> 00:05:11,606
They could even be prefab objects

134
00:05:11,666 --> 00:05:12,627
that the whole team can use.

135
00:05:14,248 --> 00:05:16,110
Next tip, denying affordance.

136
00:05:17,931 --> 00:05:19,352
While affordances are important

137
00:05:19,372 --> 00:05:21,133
at showing the player what they can interact with,

138
00:05:21,563 --> 00:05:23,984
Showing them what they cannot interact with is also important.

139
00:05:24,684 --> 00:05:25,905
This is denying affordance,

140
00:05:26,165 --> 00:05:28,225
and it prevents player frustration and guides them.

141
00:05:29,566 --> 00:05:32,547
Now, you can't just disable a ladder or place an invisible wall.

142
00:05:32,847 --> 00:05:35,108
I mean, you can, but you shouldn't,

143
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:36,928
because it's frustrating to players.

144
00:05:38,088 --> 00:05:41,029
So, you need to contextualize why you can't use the affordance

145
00:05:41,450 --> 00:05:43,430
by adding clearly visible things that say,

146
00:05:43,530 --> 00:05:45,051
can't use this, or don't go there.

147
00:05:46,691 --> 00:05:48,972
Also, make sure the reason for denied affordance

148
00:05:49,072 --> 00:05:50,112
is clear in your block mesh.

149
00:05:51,477 --> 00:05:54,780
At Naughty Dog, we record when a playtester tries to jump

150
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:56,742
and grab something that they can't grab.

151
00:05:57,282 --> 00:06:00,245
We call these bad jumps and overlay them as red spheres

152
00:06:00,285 --> 00:06:02,507
in the game so that we can identify problem areas.

153
00:06:03,228 --> 00:06:05,210
Often, we'll find something that looks climbable

154
00:06:05,250 --> 00:06:06,271
but isn't supposed to be.

155
00:06:06,771 --> 00:06:08,713
So we'll cover it with foliage or something,

156
00:06:08,793 --> 00:06:11,296
and after the next playtest, those bad jumps will be gone.

157
00:06:12,177 --> 00:06:13,458
Like sanding down a piece of wood,

158
00:06:13,798 --> 00:06:15,860
this process makes the levels play smoother.

159
00:06:17,748 --> 00:06:19,629
Here's an example of using spiky shapes

160
00:06:19,769 --> 00:06:21,470
and breaking up the horizontal edge

161
00:06:21,590 --> 00:06:22,751
to deny climbing affordance.

162
00:06:23,972 --> 00:06:26,193
Even though the window is within climbing range,

163
00:06:26,313 --> 00:06:28,715
you still can't grab it because it's visually blocked.

164
00:06:29,636 --> 00:06:31,217
Notice how this is contextualized

165
00:06:31,437 --> 00:06:33,338
to the environment with bricks and rebar.

166
00:06:34,279 --> 00:06:36,740
This is important for games grounded in reality.

167
00:06:37,681 --> 00:06:40,203
For games not so grounded, you can get away with a lot,

168
00:06:40,403 --> 00:06:41,003
and that's okay.

169
00:06:41,964 --> 00:06:43,985
Just find the right tone and context for your world

170
00:06:44,005 --> 00:06:46,086
to make it feel natural and still deny affordance.

171
00:06:46,975 --> 00:06:47,956
Now let's see some block mesh.

172
00:06:48,916 --> 00:06:50,957
Let's say that we want the player to go through the window

173
00:06:50,977 --> 00:06:52,557
on the right, which is busted open.

174
00:06:53,838 --> 00:06:55,378
The left window is covered with a bush,

175
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:59,740
and the front porch window and door are blocked with boards.

176
00:07:01,100 --> 00:07:02,581
Most players will glance at this house

177
00:07:02,661 --> 00:07:04,421
and go right for that window in a play test.

178
00:07:04,801 --> 00:07:06,342
The intended way forward is open,

179
00:07:06,662 --> 00:07:09,003
while the rest of the entrance affordances are denied.

180
00:07:11,364 --> 00:07:12,984
Next tip, shape language.

181
00:07:14,325 --> 00:07:16,205
Establishing a consistent shape language.

182
00:07:16,662 --> 00:07:18,562
communicates affordance and guides players.

183
00:07:19,983 --> 00:07:22,764
Climbing edges in Uncharted are always horizontal and flat.

184
00:07:23,365 --> 00:07:26,106
As a player, you learn this visual language

185
00:07:26,206 --> 00:07:29,648
of Ford's climbing, and you can spot it easily.

186
00:07:30,928 --> 00:07:33,249
Also, people tend to have emotional associations

187
00:07:33,549 --> 00:07:35,650
with certain types of primitive shapes, which

188
00:07:35,710 --> 00:07:38,031
is even common across cultures.

189
00:07:39,272 --> 00:07:42,534
We can use this to our advantage to guide players toward or away

190
00:07:42,594 --> 00:07:43,374
from certain shapes.

191
00:07:44,374 --> 00:07:46,235
Round shapes tend to be viewed as non-threatening.

192
00:07:46,543 --> 00:07:47,743
There's nothing to stab you with.

193
00:07:48,904 --> 00:07:51,484
Rectangular shapes are viewed as stable and trustworthy,

194
00:07:52,365 --> 00:07:52,925
like a shelter.

195
00:07:53,965 --> 00:07:56,406
And diagonal shapes are viewed as aggressive and dangerous,

196
00:07:56,526 --> 00:07:57,106
like a spear.

197
00:07:58,787 --> 00:08:00,647
Now let's take a look at a screenshot from Uncharted

198
00:08:00,667 --> 00:08:02,528
The Lost Legacy and highlight the shapes.

199
00:08:04,428 --> 00:08:07,269
As you can see, the spiky shapes feel a little bit uncomfortable,

200
00:08:07,569 --> 00:08:09,510
possibly causing you to want to avoid those areas.

201
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:13,051
The round areas aren't a threat, and they actually provide stealth.

202
00:08:13,885 --> 00:08:16,426
And the square shapes are combat cover or buildings,

203
00:08:16,646 --> 00:08:17,347
nice and stable.

204
00:08:18,087 --> 00:08:20,128
All of this subtly guides the player to the buildings.

205
00:08:20,869 --> 00:08:22,310
Now let's see what it looks like in block mesh.

206
00:08:23,751 --> 00:08:25,612
Let's say we want the players to go to the right,

207
00:08:26,052 --> 00:08:29,194
and they're being chased, so exploration will wreck pacing.

208
00:08:30,114 --> 00:08:31,315
The path sort of leads there,

209
00:08:31,575 --> 00:08:33,056
but some players may veer to the left.

210
00:08:33,276 --> 00:08:34,937
So how can we gently nudge them to the right?

211
00:08:36,598 --> 00:08:37,959
First, let's add some spiky trees

212
00:08:38,239 --> 00:08:40,100
and some other pine trees that angle toward the goal.

213
00:08:41,201 --> 00:08:42,281
Then we'll add some round bushes.

214
00:08:44,168 --> 00:08:45,428
Finally, we'll add a small building.

215
00:08:45,728 --> 00:08:46,929
And I'm not going to lie, at this point,

216
00:08:46,969 --> 00:08:47,589
I kind of feel like this.

217
00:08:50,590 --> 00:08:51,350
But with a lot less hair.

218
00:08:52,170 --> 00:08:55,091
All right, let's highlight the shapes we just added.

219
00:08:55,852 --> 00:08:58,332
The spiky shapes say danger, and they discourage going there.

220
00:08:59,253 --> 00:09:01,753
The square building implies, hey, stability is this way.

221
00:09:02,574 --> 00:09:04,414
The round stepping stones on the ground

222
00:09:04,574 --> 00:09:06,355
act as breadcrumbs to that stability.

223
00:09:06,955 --> 00:09:08,796
And the round bushes kind of act as bumpers

224
00:09:09,096 --> 00:09:10,116
to frame the play space.

225
00:09:10,756 --> 00:09:12,597
Of course, none of this prevents the player

226
00:09:12,637 --> 00:09:13,577
from going wherever they want.

227
00:09:14,287 --> 00:09:15,848
It just gently guides them where they should go.

228
00:09:17,589 --> 00:09:18,730
Next tip, color language.

229
00:09:20,771 --> 00:09:22,833
When you're trying to establish a consistent visual language

230
00:09:22,873 --> 00:09:25,514
in your affordances, shape is only half of it.

231
00:09:26,215 --> 00:09:27,896
You also need a consistent color as well.

232
00:09:29,597 --> 00:09:32,419
Adding color provides valuable context

233
00:09:32,439 --> 00:09:34,000
for an otherwise barren block mesh.

234
00:09:34,601 --> 00:09:36,522
It also adds depth if you're making a 3D game.

235
00:09:37,883 --> 00:09:40,405
Coloring also speeds up collaboration with your team,

236
00:09:40,605 --> 00:09:43,186
because at a glance, they can get it without explanation.

237
00:09:44,217 --> 00:09:46,357
Is the ground supposed to be dirt, lava, water?

238
00:09:47,997 --> 00:09:50,638
Now Naughty Dog is notorious for using contrasting colors

239
00:09:50,678 --> 00:09:52,298
to draw the eye to where you should go.

240
00:09:53,399 --> 00:09:55,199
Here we have a bright yellow sign and rail,

241
00:09:55,539 --> 00:09:58,040
and it subtly lets the player know where to put the plank.

242
00:09:58,660 --> 00:10:01,580
Most people won't question why only one rail is yellow.

243
00:10:01,980 --> 00:10:04,081
They'll just remember that they intuitively knew where to go.

244
00:10:06,141 --> 00:10:07,742
Here we have white climbable edges.

245
00:10:08,802 --> 00:10:09,882
And here are some more edges.

246
00:10:10,322 --> 00:10:11,262
But wait, these are green.

247
00:10:11,603 --> 00:10:12,663
I thought you said to be consistent.

248
00:10:13,366 --> 00:10:15,486
Well, it's not a single color that's important.

249
00:10:15,867 --> 00:10:18,247
It's using consistent color and shapes

250
00:10:18,427 --> 00:10:19,927
in the context of the environment.

251
00:10:20,568 --> 00:10:22,028
Try to blend them into the environment

252
00:10:22,048 --> 00:10:24,529
so it looks natural but still stands out.

253
00:10:25,689 --> 00:10:27,429
Let's see how color can age a block mesh.

254
00:10:28,469 --> 00:10:29,490
Here we have a gray box.

255
00:10:30,430 --> 00:10:32,530
It's not really clear where the player should go

256
00:10:32,550 --> 00:10:33,831
or where they even can go.

257
00:10:34,531 --> 00:10:36,251
Affordances are gray and they're hard to see.

258
00:10:37,171 --> 00:10:38,512
Also, what kind of environment is this?

259
00:10:38,712 --> 00:10:39,112
A desert?

260
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:40,112
An icy planet?

261
00:10:41,990 --> 00:10:43,592
First, let's add color to the affordances

262
00:10:43,792 --> 00:10:46,574
so that you can see them in the path forward, sort of.

263
00:10:47,555 --> 00:10:48,696
But we're still missing the context.

264
00:10:48,756 --> 00:10:49,577
What is this place?

265
00:10:49,797 --> 00:10:51,178
You know, everything blends together.

266
00:10:52,499 --> 00:10:52,719
Boom.

267
00:10:54,021 --> 00:10:55,582
We add color to the top of the blocks,

268
00:10:55,782 --> 00:10:57,704
and suddenly you're in a grassy, mountainous area

269
00:10:57,824 --> 00:10:58,705
with water down below.

270
00:10:59,405 --> 00:11:01,247
As you can see, adding color to your block mesh

271
00:11:01,327 --> 00:11:04,810
helps contextualize the level to the players and the teammates.

272
00:11:05,570 --> 00:11:07,752
And to further ground this on Earth, let's add some props.

273
00:11:09,454 --> 00:11:09,634
OK.

274
00:11:10,354 --> 00:11:10,475
Now.

275
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:13,381
Color is important, but it shouldn't be the only thing that you rely on

276
00:11:13,421 --> 00:11:14,961
because some players are colorblind.

277
00:11:15,402 --> 00:11:17,142
You should combine color with other techniques,

278
00:11:17,462 --> 00:11:21,863
like unique shapes and using contrasting color values rather than hues.

279
00:11:22,664 --> 00:11:25,124
Bonus points if you can get colorblind playtesters or teammates

280
00:11:25,164 --> 00:11:27,925
to help identify problems and make your game more accessible.

281
00:11:29,266 --> 00:11:30,406
Next tip, landmarks.

282
00:11:35,227 --> 00:11:36,848
There she is. That's our building.

283
00:11:37,328 --> 00:11:39,148
There's the tower.

284
00:11:40,283 --> 00:11:41,783
Here's the bridge, that's our way out of here.

285
00:11:43,744 --> 00:11:46,045
Ever wonder why game characters spend so much time pointing

286
00:11:46,085 --> 00:11:46,965
at things in the distance?

287
00:11:48,226 --> 00:11:49,246
Well, that's because they're landmarks,

288
00:11:49,486 --> 00:11:51,327
and they're a great way to orient players in your world.

289
00:11:52,467 --> 00:11:54,348
A landmark is basically just a big object

290
00:11:54,368 --> 00:11:56,669
that can be seen from far away and from different vantage

291
00:11:56,729 --> 00:11:56,989
points.

292
00:11:57,689 --> 00:11:59,390
If used correctly, players will see this object

293
00:11:59,490 --> 00:12:00,951
over and over as they get closer to it

294
00:12:01,171 --> 00:12:02,831
to let them know they're headed in the right direction.

295
00:12:04,172 --> 00:12:06,653
Landmarks also act as a goal for the player to work toward.

296
00:12:07,233 --> 00:12:08,193
They're also called weenies.

297
00:12:09,021 --> 00:12:11,902
If you want to know more about that, just Google Disney and weenies.

298
00:12:12,462 --> 00:12:13,382
Don't worry, it's safe for work.

299
00:12:14,302 --> 00:12:14,783
Probably.

300
00:12:16,263 --> 00:12:17,403
Depends if your safe search is off.

301
00:12:18,204 --> 00:12:18,964
All right, check this out.

302
00:12:19,644 --> 00:12:22,045
Zelda, the Breath of the Wild really goes nuts with the landmarks.

303
00:12:22,485 --> 00:12:25,045
In just this one shot, there are several visible all in a row,

304
00:12:25,286 --> 00:12:26,646
and they're not overlapping one another.

305
00:12:27,086 --> 00:12:29,487
They also have unique silhouettes, so you don't confuse them,

306
00:12:29,747 --> 00:12:30,867
which is also a great tip.

307
00:12:31,527 --> 00:12:33,588
Try to have unique silhouettes for things in your game,

308
00:12:33,808 --> 00:12:35,768
so that players can distinguish them at a glance.

309
00:12:37,009 --> 00:12:37,829
All right, block mesh time.

310
00:12:38,856 --> 00:12:40,637
Let's add a landmark to this block mesh.

311
00:12:42,757 --> 00:12:45,898
It's pretty basic, but it can have a huge impact

312
00:12:46,039 --> 00:12:48,019
on drawing the player toward a certain direction.

313
00:12:48,679 --> 00:12:51,400
If I'm working with a landmark, I like to add it first

314
00:12:51,460 --> 00:12:53,161
and then build the level backwards from there.

315
00:12:53,761 --> 00:12:55,342
That way I can always see it in the distance

316
00:12:55,422 --> 00:12:56,582
and shape the level accordingly.

317
00:12:57,723 --> 00:12:59,123
Next tip, openings attract.

318
00:13:00,244 --> 00:13:01,524
Caves, doors, et cetera,

319
00:13:01,724 --> 00:13:03,305
they all seem to attract people toward them.

320
00:13:04,445 --> 00:13:06,506
These openings often lead to a refuge space,

321
00:13:06,986 --> 00:13:08,326
which psychologically feels safe.

322
00:13:09,757 --> 00:13:11,579
Openings also have an air of mystery about them,

323
00:13:11,859 --> 00:13:13,160
and people want to see what's inside.

324
00:13:13,941 --> 00:13:15,522
This attraction happens in the real world

325
00:13:15,622 --> 00:13:18,084
with hobbies like spelunking and urban exploration.

326
00:13:19,705 --> 00:13:21,887
Here in Titanfall 2, a ramp affords

327
00:13:21,947 --> 00:13:24,529
jumping to a nicely lit opening that begs to be explored.

328
00:13:26,150 --> 00:13:27,651
This underwater opening lets you know

329
00:13:27,671 --> 00:13:29,353
that there's something beyond it if you swim for it.

330
00:13:31,354 --> 00:13:32,475
It even works in block worlds.

331
00:13:32,695 --> 00:13:34,137
As soon as I saw this, I went right for it.

332
00:13:36,042 --> 00:13:37,844
Doors and archways also draw you inside,

333
00:13:37,964 --> 00:13:39,705
even though an archway may not have a roof above it.

334
00:13:42,007 --> 00:13:43,688
When adding openings to block mesh,

335
00:13:43,929 --> 00:13:45,750
it's important to have different colors

336
00:13:45,810 --> 00:13:47,471
for interior and exterior walls.

337
00:13:48,352 --> 00:13:49,973
Here we have a cool white exterior

338
00:13:50,033 --> 00:13:51,134
and a warm yellow interior.

339
00:13:51,915 --> 00:13:53,796
This helps players read depth in your block mesh.

340
00:13:54,457 --> 00:13:55,938
If they're the same color, it's hard to tell

341
00:13:55,978 --> 00:13:57,099
that it's even an opening.

342
00:13:58,080 --> 00:14:00,742
Also, communicate this design intent to your artist

343
00:14:00,762 --> 00:14:02,603
to ensure that they know that this is an entrance

344
00:14:02,924 --> 00:14:03,984
and that it needs to stand out.

345
00:14:05,319 --> 00:14:08,020
Next tip, gates and valves.

346
00:14:09,601 --> 00:14:10,121
Terrible joke.

347
00:14:10,501 --> 00:14:12,062
All right, no, not those gates and valves,

348
00:14:12,162 --> 00:14:13,383
the kind that make way more money.

349
00:14:14,043 --> 00:14:15,103
We want the level design kind.

350
00:14:16,224 --> 00:14:18,905
Gates stop progress until some sort of conditions are met.

351
00:14:19,425 --> 00:14:20,366
You've killed all the enemies,

352
00:14:20,406 --> 00:14:22,366
you've moved the debris out of the way, et cetera.

353
00:14:23,247 --> 00:14:24,087
Valves are the opposite.

354
00:14:24,607 --> 00:14:25,728
They let players move forward,

355
00:14:25,808 --> 00:14:27,329
and then they slam the door shut behind them

356
00:14:27,369 --> 00:14:28,469
so they can't get backtrack.

357
00:14:29,870 --> 00:14:32,711
In this scenario, we want the player to enter the combat space

358
00:14:32,771 --> 00:14:34,152
and be trapped until combat's over.

359
00:14:35,007 --> 00:14:38,848
We have a valve into the space and then a gate at the other end blocking them so they can't leave.

360
00:14:40,048 --> 00:14:45,250
Once they enter, the gates and valves reduce the possibility space of the world to just the combat zone.

361
00:14:45,990 --> 00:14:49,591
Also, there's less mentally to keep track of so players can focus on the task at hand.

362
00:14:51,491 --> 00:14:57,233
It may look like this is only useful in linear games, but open world games can use it too with scenarios like arena battles.

363
00:14:57,773 --> 00:15:02,195
The Halo series did a great job of having big open levels that gated and valved players when needed.

364
00:15:04,150 --> 00:15:05,370
Now, gates are pretty straightforward.

365
00:15:05,510 --> 00:15:07,351
There's something in your way, and you need to clear it.

366
00:15:07,831 --> 00:15:10,251
So I'll focus on valves, which can be a little more nuanced.

367
00:15:10,712 --> 00:15:12,472
In this valve example, you drop down,

368
00:15:12,552 --> 00:15:13,512
and you can't get back up.

369
00:15:30,577 --> 00:15:32,458
A fairly famous valve is in Super Metroid.

370
00:15:33,313 --> 00:15:35,294
where an entire chunk of level acts like a valve.

371
00:15:35,914 --> 00:15:38,016
At some point, the player falls down this really long shaft,

372
00:15:38,056 --> 00:15:38,896
and there's no way back up.

373
00:15:40,197 --> 00:15:42,479
They're stuck, and the vast possibility space of the game

374
00:15:42,539 --> 00:15:45,000
is reduced to a tiny portion as seen on the map.

375
00:15:46,081 --> 00:15:48,682
In this space, they find two critical items, the high jump

376
00:15:48,702 --> 00:15:49,543
boots and the ice beam.

377
00:15:50,003 --> 00:15:52,705
And they learn to freeze enemies and then jump off of them

378
00:15:53,185 --> 00:15:54,926
so that they can use it to escape the shaft.

379
00:15:55,787 --> 00:15:57,748
The shaft that was once a valve has now

380
00:15:57,788 --> 00:15:59,209
become a gate that needs to be overcome.

381
00:16:00,411 --> 00:16:01,712
Given the entire world to explore,

382
00:16:01,752 --> 00:16:03,754
they may have never discovered this ability.

383
00:16:05,295 --> 00:16:06,576
Next tip, leading lines.

384
00:16:07,857 --> 00:16:09,558
Leading lines are a composition technique

385
00:16:09,899 --> 00:16:11,320
where lines in the environment draw the eye

386
00:16:11,360 --> 00:16:12,801
to a specific place in the scene.

387
00:16:13,722 --> 00:16:16,664
In this photo, the logs dry the eye up and into the frame

388
00:16:16,904 --> 00:16:18,045
to finally rest on the house.

389
00:16:19,306 --> 00:16:21,268
In games, these are often things like roads and pipes

390
00:16:21,308 --> 00:16:22,589
and cables and all sorts of stuff.

391
00:16:23,830 --> 00:16:25,411
Here in Titanfall 2, we wanted the player

392
00:16:25,431 --> 00:16:27,373
to focus on this door and not miss the reveal

393
00:16:27,393 --> 00:16:27,953
of a new enemy.

394
00:16:28,964 --> 00:16:31,085
Pipes and floor grates form leading lines to the door.

395
00:16:32,426 --> 00:16:34,368
And when you get close, a stalker rips the door open

396
00:16:34,388 --> 00:16:35,269
for a grand reveal.

397
00:16:37,230 --> 00:16:39,512
Here in the block mesh is a hallway with a T-junction

398
00:16:39,552 --> 00:16:39,952
at the end.

399
00:16:40,973 --> 00:16:42,895
Let's say you wanted the player to go to the right again.

400
00:16:43,695 --> 00:16:44,996
Right now, it's a coin toss.

401
00:16:45,577 --> 00:16:48,519
They may turn left, see a locked door and turn around,

402
00:16:48,899 --> 00:16:51,261
or they may smoothly go to the right and enter the next area.

403
00:16:52,442 --> 00:16:53,743
By adding some leading lines, though,

404
00:16:54,023 --> 00:16:55,365
we can draw their attention to the right

405
00:16:55,745 --> 00:16:57,106
and increase the chances they'll go there.

406
00:16:57,853 --> 00:17:01,095
Pipes on the walls and rug guide the player down the hallway.

407
00:17:02,236 --> 00:17:04,937
But the pipes on the left stop while the pipes on the right

408
00:17:04,977 --> 00:17:06,878
go along around the corner, drawing the eye.

409
00:17:08,139 --> 00:17:10,940
The caution cones break up the red line of the rug going left.

410
00:17:12,261 --> 00:17:15,542
And to go over the top, we add a big, bright yellow cable

411
00:17:15,942 --> 00:17:18,284
that hugs the right side and goes along around the corner.

412
00:17:18,844 --> 00:17:21,205
Just some simple shapes, but it can have a huge impact

413
00:17:21,365 --> 00:17:23,206
on smooth navigation in your play tests.

414
00:17:24,407 --> 00:17:25,227
Next tip, pinching.

415
00:17:27,044 --> 00:17:28,905
Pinching basically means your layout funnels the player

416
00:17:28,945 --> 00:17:29,845
to a specific spot.

417
00:17:30,325 --> 00:17:33,166
You accomplish this by blocking off areas and angling shapes

418
00:17:33,206 --> 00:17:35,767
to naturally flow to that spot.

419
00:17:36,047 --> 00:17:38,228
It's good for redirecting players to a specific area.

420
00:17:38,788 --> 00:17:40,829
And it's also a great way to set up a cool reveal,

421
00:17:41,890 --> 00:17:43,490
like the view of a landmark, without forcing

422
00:17:43,530 --> 00:17:44,490
the camera to look at it.

423
00:17:45,111 --> 00:17:46,831
If you pinch them to a specific spot,

424
00:17:47,211 --> 00:17:48,672
the camera will be naturally pointed

425
00:17:48,732 --> 00:17:49,772
at the thing you want them to see.

426
00:17:52,814 --> 00:17:53,374
Wrong slide.

427
00:17:53,454 --> 00:17:53,514
OK.

428
00:17:53,534 --> 00:17:54,254
There we go.

429
00:17:54,860 --> 00:17:57,642
Of course, all of this completely depends on your mobility mechanics.

430
00:17:58,042 --> 00:18:00,883
It's much easier to do this in a game where players are stuck on the ground

431
00:18:01,143 --> 00:18:03,444
than in something like Titanfall where they're flying all over the place.

432
00:18:04,365 --> 00:18:05,305
Let's look at an example.

433
00:18:06,546 --> 00:18:08,967
Here, the buses and cars are angled to a specific spot,

434
00:18:09,807 --> 00:18:10,948
which you can see highlighted here.

435
00:18:12,369 --> 00:18:16,651
Walking down the street, the shapes naturally bring you to the end of the pinch,

436
00:18:17,071 --> 00:18:18,672
which faces the way forward.

437
00:18:20,192 --> 00:18:21,033
Let's see it in action.

438
00:18:21,675 --> 00:18:25,658
In this video, the pinch lines up a perfect shot of the hospital in the distance, which is your goal,

439
00:18:26,298 --> 00:18:27,379
and the tunnel that takes you there.

440
00:18:41,350 --> 00:18:42,831
Next tip, framing and composition.

441
00:18:44,472 --> 00:18:46,473
Another technique borrowed from photography.

442
00:18:46,974 --> 00:18:51,457
By framing your subject, be it a landmark, a big enemy, or a cave opening, you draw attention to it.

443
00:18:52,465 --> 00:18:54,448
If you'd like to learn more, just Google some photography

444
00:18:54,508 --> 00:18:56,310
composition techniques, you'll find lots of stuff.

445
00:18:58,193 --> 00:19:00,155
This one's really useful when combined with pinching

446
00:19:00,316 --> 00:19:01,918
to set up an important reveal on the level.

447
00:19:02,518 --> 00:19:04,521
After you pinch the player to a specific spot,

448
00:19:05,022 --> 00:19:07,845
perfectly frame the object for maximum effect.

449
00:19:08,546 --> 00:19:09,367
Let's see it in action.

450
00:19:18,712 --> 00:19:21,213
As you saw, the player is naturally pointed at the dam,

451
00:19:21,333 --> 00:19:23,815
and due to good framing, it was the dominant thing on screen.

452
00:19:24,495 --> 00:19:27,476
Also, a side tip, people's eyes are drawn to detail,

453
00:19:27,596 --> 00:19:28,857
and the dam is very detailed.

454
00:19:29,877 --> 00:19:31,198
All of this with just some layout

455
00:19:31,298 --> 00:19:32,359
and no forced camera moves.

456
00:19:34,019 --> 00:19:35,560
All right, next tip, breadcrumbs.

457
00:19:36,260 --> 00:19:36,941
Aw, yes.

458
00:19:39,062 --> 00:19:40,702
Breadcrumbs lead the player a little piece

459
00:19:40,722 --> 00:19:41,623
at a time to the goal.

460
00:19:42,723 --> 00:19:43,644
They can be almost anything,

461
00:19:43,744 --> 00:19:44,844
chunks of stuff on the ground,

462
00:19:45,004 --> 00:19:48,266
pickup items, enemies, lit areas, et cetera.

463
00:19:49,205 --> 00:19:51,686
It's usually better to add breadcrumbs to your block mesh

464
00:19:51,866 --> 00:19:53,686
after the early play tests, because they

465
00:19:53,727 --> 00:19:55,907
can hide fundamental layout guidance problems.

466
00:19:56,647 --> 00:19:58,508
But if you still need them after a few revisions,

467
00:19:58,548 --> 00:19:59,588
don't feel bad about adding them.

468
00:20:00,868 --> 00:20:03,009
In this example, the bits on the fence and roof

469
00:20:03,269 --> 00:20:05,410
create a visual stepping stones to the ledge.

470
00:20:07,050 --> 00:20:09,951
In Destiny 2, these panels guide the player into the tunnel.

471
00:20:11,711 --> 00:20:13,932
Now, if your game has pickups, they're

472
00:20:13,952 --> 00:20:15,732
a classic way to breadcrumb players around the level.

473
00:20:16,290 --> 00:20:18,170
Like how many times have you played a Mario game

474
00:20:18,350 --> 00:20:19,871
and the coins led you to a new area?

475
00:20:21,452 --> 00:20:23,912
Pickups are also great for letting players know they're on the right path

476
00:20:24,012 --> 00:20:25,573
in a cluttered or maze-like environment.

477
00:20:26,113 --> 00:20:28,474
This one's placed next to an area that you can duck under,

478
00:20:28,574 --> 00:20:30,315
which some players forget they can even do,

479
00:20:30,835 --> 00:20:32,935
so it subtly hints, yep, you're going the right way.

480
00:20:34,976 --> 00:20:35,997
So to go back to this house,

481
00:20:36,417 --> 00:20:39,398
let's say only half the players during our last playtest went into the house,

482
00:20:39,718 --> 00:20:40,858
and the other half got lost.

483
00:20:42,259 --> 00:20:44,960
Let's add some rocks and boards as breadcrumbs leading to the window.

484
00:20:45,571 --> 00:20:47,571
Notice how the boards are angled toward the window,

485
00:20:47,671 --> 00:20:48,612
creating leading lines.

486
00:20:49,652 --> 00:20:52,413
You can also sprinkle these breadcrumbs in open world areas

487
00:20:52,513 --> 00:20:53,973
to lead players to interesting things,

488
00:20:54,173 --> 00:20:55,813
like the panels in the Destiny example.

489
00:20:57,394 --> 00:20:58,374
Next tip, textures.

490
00:20:59,474 --> 00:21:02,115
You can use textures to subtly, or sometimes obviously,

491
00:21:02,175 --> 00:21:03,015
point the way to a goal.

492
00:21:03,775 --> 00:21:04,896
These can be just about anything.

493
00:21:05,156 --> 00:21:08,076
Arrows, scrapes on the wall, signs, et cetera.

494
00:21:08,897 --> 00:21:10,377
Here in Uncharted, The Lost Legacy,

495
00:21:11,217 --> 00:21:13,238
scrape textures on the wall communicate affordance

496
00:21:13,418 --> 00:21:14,198
that you can shimmy here.

497
00:21:15,018 --> 00:21:17,400
This example leads to a secret area and a collectible.

498
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:19,642
So it's a good example that you don't need to do this

499
00:21:19,702 --> 00:21:20,743
for just the main path.

500
00:21:22,765 --> 00:21:23,345
Here in Uncharted 4,

501
00:21:24,767 --> 00:21:26,288
these tire tracks on the rock

502
00:21:26,448 --> 00:21:28,030
communicate a fordance that you can drive here.

503
00:21:28,730 --> 00:21:29,651
Now when I played this game,

504
00:21:29,791 --> 00:21:31,573
I didn't notice the tire tracks and I got lost.

505
00:21:32,614 --> 00:21:33,314
I didn't work on this game.

506
00:21:35,196 --> 00:21:35,897
I worked on the next one.

507
00:21:38,099 --> 00:21:39,520
Once I noticed the tire tracks, though,

508
00:21:39,560 --> 00:21:41,102
the rest of it driving went totally smoothly.

509
00:21:42,504 --> 00:21:44,385
Signs literally point the way to the hospital,

510
00:21:44,505 --> 00:21:45,345
which is also your goal.

511
00:21:46,466 --> 00:21:48,527
These textures are often some of the last things added

512
00:21:48,587 --> 00:21:50,568
when making a level, so it doesn't,

