693
00:29:41,294 --> 00:29:43,795
so you won't see much sun in the next few days.

694
00:29:44,896 --> 00:29:48,197
There's also fire, controlled burning in gas lamps,

695
00:29:48,457 --> 00:29:50,298
incandescent light bulbs with filament

696
00:29:50,358 --> 00:29:51,719
and run current through the filament.

697
00:29:52,126 --> 00:29:56,569
There's also a stronger focus these days on energy efficient light sources like

698
00:29:56,669 --> 00:30:00,272
fluorescent lighting or LED lighting is also becoming more common.

699
00:30:01,292 --> 00:30:07,276
And I think it's very tempting to think of this as a story about technology and

700
00:30:07,356 --> 00:30:12,380
progress and older light sources becoming obsolete or something.

701
00:30:12,460 --> 00:30:16,423
But that's not exactly true, and I don't think that's exactly accurate.

702
00:30:16,523 --> 00:30:20,325
Like the light bulb did not make the sun obsolete.

703
00:30:20,775 --> 00:30:24,978
Right? Like you still like going outside and playing in the sun or whatever you do in the sun.

704
00:30:25,659 --> 00:30:28,401
Um, I wouldn't, no, I'm a game developer. But, um,

705
00:30:29,101 --> 00:30:32,484
the LED did not make the fire obsolete.

706
00:30:32,944 --> 00:30:35,966
Right? Uh, you'll go to a restaurant and

707
00:30:36,266 --> 00:30:39,589
maybe tonight and have a nice candle lit dinner or something

708
00:30:40,229 --> 00:30:42,531
and the flickering candle,

709
00:30:42,831 --> 00:30:47,795
it's really nice when that's actual fire, not one of those weird LED flickering things. Right?

710
00:30:50,661 --> 00:30:57,204
So as a society, I think we still use fire as a light source, not necessarily as a task

711
00:30:57,485 --> 00:31:00,466
light source where you write letters by candlelight or something.

712
00:31:01,067 --> 00:31:04,388
But it's still in our birthday candles, our campfires.

713
00:31:05,169 --> 00:31:09,871
Fire hasn't disappeared, but our culture around fire has changed.

714
00:31:10,351 --> 00:31:14,013
Fire used to be common, and now it's more like a special occasion kind of thing.

715
00:31:14,133 --> 00:31:16,435
But it's still here in civilization.

716
00:31:17,644 --> 00:31:22,305
So each of these light sources means something different and makes a space feel different,

717
00:31:22,885 --> 00:31:27,126
and I urge you to pay attention to the different moods and atmospheres these different light

718
00:31:27,166 --> 00:31:27,846
sources evoke.

719
00:31:30,867 --> 00:31:37,468
And today, contemporary lighting design has been kind of heavily standardized and industrialized.

720
00:31:38,368 --> 00:31:43,089
If you're a lighting designer and you're shopping for light fixtures or luminaires,

721
00:31:43,350 --> 00:31:44,130
as they're called in Europe,

722
00:31:44,830 --> 00:31:50,453
It's very common to, on the left right there, that's like a picture of like a lighting catalog.

723
00:31:51,193 --> 00:31:54,355
And the lighting catalog gives you all these different stats so you can kind of predict

724
00:31:54,435 --> 00:31:55,336
what the light will do.

725
00:31:56,156 --> 00:31:59,798
And there's also usually often like a chart in that lower left.

726
00:31:59,998 --> 00:32:02,019
I've blown up the chart on the right there.

727
00:32:03,540 --> 00:32:05,441
And that's a light distribution curve chart.

728
00:32:05,581 --> 00:32:09,023
And that kind of shows you how much light that light source or light fixture is going

729
00:32:09,043 --> 00:32:11,745
to throw at every given angle.

730
00:32:12,282 --> 00:32:15,645
So notice this light bulb with that light distribution chart on the right.

731
00:32:16,366 --> 00:32:20,129
It's kind of shaped like a heart a little bit and has like a crease at the top.

732
00:32:20,469 --> 00:32:22,010
Well, that makes sense, right?

733
00:32:22,050 --> 00:32:24,372
Because the light socket is on top.

734
00:32:24,532 --> 00:32:27,094
It's not gonna throw light through the light socket.

735
00:32:27,134 --> 00:32:27,915
That doesn't make sense.

736
00:32:27,935 --> 00:32:30,257
So it's mainly throwing light downwards and to the right.

737
00:32:30,337 --> 00:32:33,660
So now you know how to read a light distribution chart.

738
00:32:33,680 --> 00:32:34,380
It's pretty easy.

739
00:32:36,470 --> 00:32:42,776
So this is how real life lighting design quantifies and standardizes the physics of light.

740
00:32:43,356 --> 00:32:46,979
But in video games, light is often much messier than this.

741
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:53,624
So now I want to talk a little bit about what is game lighting and what do we mean by that.

742
00:32:55,866 --> 00:33:02,552
Light is a complex phenomenon that's hopefully elegant with like a unified theorem and all

743
00:33:02,592 --> 00:33:02,792
that.

744
00:33:05,391 --> 00:33:09,212
all these phenomena like reflections, occlusion,

745
00:33:09,272 --> 00:33:12,513
translucence, shadows, all those happen in real life

746
00:33:12,653 --> 00:33:14,654
like for free, so to speak.

747
00:33:15,514 --> 00:33:19,356
But in video games, lighting is like a bunch of crap

748
00:33:19,396 --> 00:33:22,877
in a box, we don't, it's just a bunch of random systems

749
00:33:22,937 --> 00:33:24,738
that we like hack and tune together,

750
00:33:25,258 --> 00:33:26,938
and we throw all that crap in a video game

751
00:33:26,978 --> 00:33:29,599
and then pray it'll look okay in the end.

752
00:33:30,339 --> 00:33:32,760
So it's not a beautiful, elegant system,

753
00:33:33,120 --> 00:33:34,601
it's just a bunch of random stuff.

754
00:33:35,469 --> 00:33:37,950
And to give you an idea of all that random stuff, right?

755
00:33:38,590 --> 00:33:40,171
In any given game engine, there's

756
00:33:40,452 --> 00:33:43,153
different cascading shadow maps, there's refraction shaders,

757
00:33:43,213 --> 00:33:46,775
there's caustics, there's fog, there's glow sprites, HDR,

758
00:33:47,316 --> 00:33:49,557
screen space ambient occlusion, bloom.

759
00:33:49,697 --> 00:33:52,459
All these different things are all kind

760
00:33:52,579 --> 00:33:54,380
of representing one system.

761
00:33:54,520 --> 00:33:57,762
But in a video game, it's like 20 different systems, right?

762
00:33:58,363 --> 00:34:00,544
And we kind of just turn them on and turn them off

763
00:34:00,604 --> 00:34:02,285
on a case-by-case basis.

764
00:34:03,063 --> 00:34:05,105
when you play a video game, maybe when you go in this room,

765
00:34:05,365 --> 00:34:09,387
that's when they turn on some screen space reflection.

766
00:34:09,707 --> 00:34:10,968
And then when you go in this other room,

767
00:34:10,988 --> 00:34:12,809
they turn off screen space reflection

768
00:34:12,849 --> 00:34:15,030
to save on frame rate and optimize it and stuff.

769
00:34:16,010 --> 00:34:18,712
And again, from a physics perspective,

770
00:34:18,932 --> 00:34:20,733
that makes zero sense, right?

771
00:34:20,773 --> 00:34:23,934
The idea that you can turn off shadows in real life

772
00:34:24,755 --> 00:34:28,377
makes no sense, because that would just be like,

773
00:34:28,417 --> 00:34:30,017
you should go see a doctor if that happens.

774
00:34:30,217 --> 00:34:30,818
That's not good.

775
00:34:32,125 --> 00:34:36,129
So again, video games, we rely on this piecemeal approach

776
00:34:36,189 --> 00:34:37,831
of all this random stuff together.

777
00:34:39,373 --> 00:34:41,495
So in this talk, I'm not going to be talking

778
00:34:41,815 --> 00:34:43,256
about a lot of those effects.

779
00:34:43,377 --> 00:34:44,738
I'm going to be focusing on what I

780
00:34:44,778 --> 00:34:48,382
view as the fundamentals of lighting in level design, which

781
00:34:48,702 --> 00:34:50,944
are basically these four basic light types,

782
00:34:51,004 --> 00:34:53,987
directional light, spotlight, ambient light, and point light.

783
00:34:57,033 --> 00:35:01,274
So let's say you're mocking up a level in Unity or something,

784
00:35:01,594 --> 00:35:03,834
and you don't have any lights going on.

785
00:35:03,894 --> 00:35:06,395
It's just a dark level, no lights there yet.

786
00:35:06,995 --> 00:35:08,556
And I just have a bunch of blocks there.

787
00:35:10,936 --> 00:35:13,277
So first you might add some ambient light.

788
00:35:13,577 --> 00:35:17,178
Ambient light is a kind of default amount of light

789
00:35:17,218 --> 00:35:18,418
you might add to a scene.

790
00:35:18,618 --> 00:35:20,478
It refers to the whole scene.

791
00:35:20,538 --> 00:35:21,258
It's global.

792
00:35:21,979 --> 00:35:24,959
And you do that to make sure those shadows in your levels

793
00:35:25,079 --> 00:35:26,200
aren't pitch black.

794
00:35:26,743 --> 00:35:30,964
because in real life, very few things are just pitch black like that,

795
00:35:30,984 --> 00:35:33,065
unless you're in a really dark cave or something.

796
00:35:33,285 --> 00:35:36,265
There's always a little bit of light bouncing around everywhere.

797
00:35:36,606 --> 00:35:39,806
So ambient light is kind of meant to simulate that a little bit.

798
00:35:40,706 --> 00:35:42,307
But notice when we add ambient light,

799
00:35:42,507 --> 00:35:45,367
that doesn't really help us read the shapes or anything.

800
00:35:45,647 --> 00:35:47,508
It's still very flat, right?

801
00:35:48,168 --> 00:35:50,989
You still can't really see the shapes that well,

802
00:35:51,089 --> 00:35:53,149
but you can just distinguish the silhouette.

803
00:35:55,029 --> 00:35:57,190
So that's when you might add another light source.

804
00:35:57,611 --> 00:35:59,552
So here's a directional light.

805
00:35:59,612 --> 00:36:01,793
Directional light is a global light source.

806
00:36:02,093 --> 00:36:05,115
It illuminates the entire scene at once from one given

807
00:36:05,175 --> 00:36:05,876
direction.

808
00:36:06,636 --> 00:36:07,877
And it usually doesn't matter where

809
00:36:07,897 --> 00:36:09,398
you position a directional light,

810
00:36:09,518 --> 00:36:10,839
depending on what tool you're using.

811
00:36:11,439 --> 00:36:12,560
And now with the directional light,

812
00:36:12,580 --> 00:36:15,041
you can read the shapes much more clearly,

813
00:36:15,061 --> 00:36:17,403
because you add that directionality component

814
00:36:17,443 --> 00:36:17,903
to it now.

815
00:36:18,404 --> 00:36:20,165
And notice how everything pops out more.

816
00:36:21,030 --> 00:36:22,712
In games, we usually use directional light,

817
00:36:22,812 --> 00:36:25,554
usually for sunlight or maybe moonlight or something.

818
00:36:27,596 --> 00:36:28,816
Then we also have a spotlight.

819
00:36:28,836 --> 00:36:31,198
If the scene is set at night, maybe you

820
00:36:31,218 --> 00:36:32,499
want to add some street lights.

821
00:36:33,220 --> 00:36:35,302
For a street light, you might want to use a spotlight.

822
00:36:35,322 --> 00:36:38,764
A spotlight throws light in a cone shape in a given direction

823
00:36:39,385 --> 00:36:40,706
and from a given position.

824
00:36:40,786 --> 00:36:43,428
So here I'm using a spotlight as a down light

825
00:36:43,628 --> 00:36:46,410
to emphasize this walkable floor area instead

826
00:36:46,470 --> 00:36:47,931
of emphasizing something else.

827
00:36:50,943 --> 00:36:53,383
And lastly, I want to talk about the point light.

828
00:36:53,564 --> 00:36:55,724
The point light throws light in every direction.

829
00:36:56,164 --> 00:36:59,045
Some tool sets might call this an omnidirectional light,

830
00:36:59,145 --> 00:37:01,265
or you can call it an omni light for short,

831
00:37:01,305 --> 00:37:03,146
which makes it sound really cool, omni light.

832
00:37:03,486 --> 00:37:08,247
But you imagine a point light as this invisible ball of light

833
00:37:08,547 --> 00:37:11,208
that's just washing everything nearby with light.

834
00:37:12,188 --> 00:37:13,908
So a point light, I think, is usually

835
00:37:13,948 --> 00:37:16,509
really good at drawing attention to a focal point,

836
00:37:16,769 --> 00:37:19,049
because it ends up creating kind of this hot spot

837
00:37:19,149 --> 00:37:19,990
effect a little bit.

838
00:37:21,918 --> 00:37:26,821
In contrast with a spotlight, right, it's not always clear where the spotlight is shining from,

839
00:37:26,881 --> 00:37:30,843
especially if it's a spotlight like a floodlight shooting light across.

840
00:37:33,244 --> 00:37:36,546
And in practice, you should try to use all four lighting types at once

841
00:37:36,566 --> 00:37:39,107
because they all can work together really well.

842
00:37:39,467 --> 00:37:41,028
Ambient helps bring up the shadows.

843
00:37:41,308 --> 00:37:43,769
Directional light helps make those background buildings pop

844
00:37:44,170 --> 00:37:46,431
and helps guide the main mood of the scene.

845
00:37:46,873 --> 00:37:49,094
Then you also have a spotlight highlighting an area.

846
00:37:49,334 --> 00:37:51,515
Then you also have a point light highlighting the streetlight.

847
00:37:51,895 --> 00:37:54,916
And again, all this stuff works together, helps create depth.

848
00:37:55,856 --> 00:37:59,938
It helps push a background and a foreground for your scene.

849
00:38:00,578 --> 00:38:01,939
And that's good.

850
00:38:03,399 --> 00:38:07,240
And with these light sources, I would

851
00:38:07,400 --> 00:38:10,862
argue that they form a complete domain of lighting tools.

852
00:38:12,070 --> 00:38:16,212
So stretching this gamut from like a global light source that affects

853
00:38:16,332 --> 00:38:20,615
everything to a local light source that only affects nearby things or a light

854
00:38:20,635 --> 00:38:25,117
source that shines in one direction or all directions I feel like it's like a

855
00:38:25,157 --> 00:38:30,200
complete domain kind of. So the kind again that's why every 3d engine or

856
00:38:30,240 --> 00:38:32,861
tool set usually has these light sources.

857
00:38:36,643 --> 00:38:40,806
So now we should talk a little bit about why we how we should use these light

858
00:38:40,826 --> 00:38:41,166
sources.

859
00:38:42,022 --> 00:38:47,804
And I'm going to talk about a lighting theory called three-point lighting, which is a very

860
00:38:47,944 --> 00:38:54,566
common form of lighting design theory that's very common in film and photography.

861
00:38:54,666 --> 00:38:57,528
So if you have a background in that, this will seem very familiar to you.

862
00:38:59,448 --> 00:39:03,110
Basic idea of three-point lighting is that you have three different light types.

863
00:39:03,942 --> 00:39:08,005
And here's a diagram that hopefully explains some of it.

864
00:39:08,285 --> 00:39:11,087
In that top left, we have a combined composite

865
00:39:11,387 --> 00:39:12,668
of three different light types.

866
00:39:12,988 --> 00:39:15,590
But we can also break down what each light is doing

867
00:39:15,610 --> 00:39:16,811
into a separate channel.

868
00:39:17,091 --> 00:39:20,033
So that's what those other three smaller pictures are doing.

869
00:39:20,833 --> 00:39:23,275
And in the top right, you have a key light.

870
00:39:23,555 --> 00:39:25,756
The key light is kind of like your brightest light source.

871
00:39:26,297 --> 00:39:29,699
And it kind of sets the dominant lighting angle and mood

872
00:39:29,759 --> 00:39:31,760
for your scene or picture or image.

873
00:39:32,443 --> 00:39:34,804
Then in the bottom left, we have a fill light.

874
00:39:35,245 --> 00:39:37,585
A fill light helps brighten up the shadows,

875
00:39:37,625 --> 00:39:39,866
kind of like the ambient light we were talking about before,

876
00:39:40,126 --> 00:39:42,487
and helps fill in the darker parts.

877
00:39:42,947 --> 00:39:44,968
Usually you want this at a lower intensity

878
00:39:45,008 --> 00:39:46,009
than your key light.

879
00:39:47,149 --> 00:39:50,210
Then in the lower right, we have the rim light.

880
00:39:50,950 --> 00:39:54,532
And it's also sometimes called a back light or a hair light,

881
00:39:54,572 --> 00:39:55,652
depending on what you're doing.

882
00:39:56,149 --> 00:40:00,451
And it illuminates your silhouette to help pop it out from the background very faintly.

883
00:40:00,512 --> 00:40:04,154
Otherwise the hair might end up, or the top of the head might be blending in with the

884
00:40:04,194 --> 00:40:04,634
background.

885
00:40:04,674 --> 00:40:08,597
So notice they do some specular and stuff on top like that.

886
00:40:11,059 --> 00:40:15,642
And a very common three-point kind of setup might end up looking a little bit like this.

887
00:40:16,603 --> 00:40:19,945
You have a key light and fill light, usually kind of at opposing angles.

888
00:40:20,185 --> 00:40:24,488
Usually don't want them falling the same direction and position, because then that kind of defeats

889
00:40:24,528 --> 00:40:24,988
the purpose.

890
00:40:25,589 --> 00:40:30,111
So usually you want fill and key to be at least different angles and positions.

891
00:40:31,391 --> 00:40:36,993
And in film and photography, there's also often the background light, that optional light right there.

892
00:40:37,673 --> 00:40:43,496
The background light helps brighten the background to help get rid of any awkward shadows that come from the key and fill.

893
00:40:43,516 --> 00:40:46,917
Remember, in real life, they can't just turn off shadows for the key and fill.

894
00:40:47,197 --> 00:40:49,858
They actually have to have another light to get rid of that shadow.

895
00:40:53,981 --> 00:40:58,865
And if you basically watch any movie, you can kind of break down any given film shot

896
00:40:59,286 --> 00:41:03,309
along these lines and try to see what all the different light sources are doing.

897
00:41:03,749 --> 00:41:06,872
So these are some examples from a blog called Lighting Pixels.

898
00:41:07,493 --> 00:41:11,236
You can see there's a key light, a fill light, and a rim light on that left.

899
00:41:11,896 --> 00:41:15,540
The key light is kind of coming from that top left of that image.

900
00:41:16,280 --> 00:41:18,602
So then it kind of feels like sunlight, kind of.

901
00:41:19,484 --> 00:41:24,025
And everything in that image is kind of evenly illuminated too, so it seems very readable.

902
00:41:24,726 --> 00:41:28,587
Meanwhile, on the right, the key light is not coming from the top, right?

903
00:41:28,627 --> 00:41:33,269
The key light is coming from below, which means it's probably not sunlight, unless these

904
00:41:33,289 --> 00:41:36,350
people are like hanging upside down, that's probably not sunlight, right?

905
00:41:36,850 --> 00:41:41,952
So to me, that means it's more like an artificial light source, maybe like a nice candle or

906
00:41:42,012 --> 00:41:42,452
something.

907
00:41:42,973 --> 00:41:43,433
And when that...

908
00:41:43,855 --> 00:41:50,898
candles illuminating from Bama's face. I feel like that sets up a very different mood in the right image versus the left image, right?

909
00:41:51,239 --> 00:41:53,740
the right image feels kind of more intimate and

910
00:41:55,120 --> 00:42:00,303
Maybe even like romantic. I don't know what movie that's from. Maybe maybe they're breaking up or having a divorce

911
00:42:00,443 --> 00:42:06,685
I don't know some some shit is going down in that right image, right? But in the left image zero shit, right?

912
00:42:06,725 --> 00:42:09,326
It's very very nice and safe

913
00:42:13,885 --> 00:42:17,786
And it's really important to note that with three-point lighting,

914
00:42:18,326 --> 00:42:21,227
it's referring to three types of light sources.

915
00:42:21,487 --> 00:42:24,327
You don't always need to place three lights in every scene.

916
00:42:24,767 --> 00:42:27,168
So, for example, in that film shot on the left,

917
00:42:27,428 --> 00:42:30,268
there's only two light sources there, a key light and a rim.

918
00:42:30,308 --> 00:42:34,709
There's no fill, and the right side of his face is left in shadow.

919
00:42:34,989 --> 00:42:37,510
And that's OK if that's what you want to do with your lighting,

920
00:42:37,530 --> 00:42:39,690
and that's the mood you want to create.

921
00:42:39,750 --> 00:42:40,831
Same thing in that right image.

922
00:42:40,951 --> 00:42:42,851
There's only one light source, just one key.

923
00:42:43,546 --> 00:42:47,447
to help kind of emphasize, I think, the extreme close-up and intimacy of that shot.

924
00:42:49,127 --> 00:42:53,188
So, again, it's just about what you want to do with your lights

925
00:42:53,248 --> 00:42:54,489
and what you want your lights to say.

926
00:42:56,929 --> 00:42:58,070
So, here's another example.

927
00:42:58,130 --> 00:43:02,311
I mean, Unity, say you want to light this hunky dude with three-point light theory.

928
00:43:03,171 --> 00:43:06,912
The way I lit him, I had a key light kind of grazing him a little bit

929
00:43:06,972 --> 00:43:08,872
so I could catch some muscle definition.

930
00:43:09,797 --> 00:43:13,920
And I had the fill light kind of a little off angle from there

931
00:43:14,020 --> 00:43:16,241
because I still wanted to maintain the key,

932
00:43:16,261 --> 00:43:18,622
but I wanted to soften how the shadows were hitting him.

933
00:43:19,363 --> 00:43:22,905
If you see in the right, that's a variant

934
00:43:22,945 --> 00:43:24,065
without the fill light.

935
00:43:24,105 --> 00:43:26,607
And without the fill light, I felt like his face

936
00:43:26,667 --> 00:43:28,228
was too much in shadow, and I couldn't

937
00:43:28,268 --> 00:43:29,288
read what was going on.

938
00:43:30,049 --> 00:43:31,810
And if you're like a beginner level designer,

939
00:43:31,830 --> 00:43:36,492
I would say most beginners forget to do the fill part.

940
00:43:36,921 --> 00:43:40,963
And if you're starting out, you should air on the side of more fill than less fill.

941
00:43:42,844 --> 00:43:48,526
And then lastly, I have a rim light also kind of picking out the right side of his face there

942
00:43:48,546 --> 00:43:51,908
and help separating that from the background so you can read his features better.

943
00:43:53,789 --> 00:43:58,471
And as for implementation, here I'm actually using three directional lights in Unity.

944
00:43:59,192 --> 00:44:02,813
but just with the layer mask set to just one layer

945
00:44:03,393 --> 00:44:04,553
just for that object.

946
00:44:04,633 --> 00:44:06,514
So it ends up being not that expensive

947
00:44:06,854 --> 00:44:08,214
if you use the culling masks.

948
00:44:09,254 --> 00:44:11,654
In Unreal, you can use a feature called light channels,

949
00:44:11,774 --> 00:44:12,955
which kind of does the same thing.

950
00:44:13,035 --> 00:44:16,215
It's super useful for isolating light sources for objects.

951
00:44:16,935 --> 00:44:19,316
But most games end up doing

952
00:44:19,756 --> 00:44:21,696
just maybe one light source technically,

953
00:44:21,976 --> 00:44:24,116
with the key light might be your main directional light,

954
00:44:24,517 --> 00:44:28,297
but your fill might be ambient or spheric harmonics probes.

955
00:44:28,741 --> 00:44:32,903
and then your rim light might be Fresnel and reflection and stuff in your shader.

956
00:44:36,185 --> 00:44:40,588
But I think there's one big problem with three-point light theory for games,

957
00:44:40,768 --> 00:44:42,609
especially in regards to level design,

958
00:44:43,270 --> 00:44:46,912
and that is the fact that film and photography

959
00:44:47,092 --> 00:44:49,934
have a very tightly controlled camera perspective,

960
00:44:50,374 --> 00:44:53,776
but in video games, we often give camera control to the player.

961
00:44:54,496 --> 00:44:54,776
So...

962
00:44:55,480 --> 00:45:13,894
If you were looking at this hunky dude and then you walk around and and admire the back of this hunky dude now the key light isn't a key light anymore because the viewing angle has changed now my rim light is like a key light now my fill light isn't visible or something I don't even know what's going on in that image anymore so.

963
00:45:15,175 --> 00:45:23,442
One big problem here is that we can't really know where the player is going to see this object which will affect how we compose our lighting.

964
00:45:25,378 --> 00:45:28,139
This is why a lot of 3D games I think end up vomiting

965
00:45:28,319 --> 00:45:30,440
rim shaders and Fresnel effects everywhere

966
00:45:30,460 --> 00:45:34,102
because they can't predict where the player is going to be looking at this object

967
00:45:34,182 --> 00:45:37,203
so they just spam Fresnel and rim everywhere

968
00:45:37,464 --> 00:45:40,705
so that there's always some rim action going on.

969
00:45:40,845 --> 00:45:43,586
But, you know, that should be your last resort.

970
00:45:43,626 --> 00:45:45,307
Let's try to be more subtle than that.

971
00:45:47,008 --> 00:45:49,649
And I would argue the way you can be more subtle

972
00:45:49,889 --> 00:45:53,031
is to think about how your level layout will facilitate

973
00:45:53,616 --> 00:45:55,797
the viewing angles for your subjects.

974
00:45:56,198 --> 00:45:58,459
And then you can light accordingly and use that

975
00:45:58,499 --> 00:45:59,560
as a framing device.

976
00:46:00,200 --> 00:46:03,442
So your level layout is a lighting tool.

977
00:46:04,323 --> 00:46:07,745
You can suggest a view or frame a certain composition

978
00:46:08,625 --> 00:46:11,047
just by having the player move through a hallway,

979
00:46:11,087 --> 00:46:12,828
and that'll suggest an angle for them.

980
00:46:14,389 --> 00:46:17,971
That's also why you need to do a little bit of block out

981
00:46:18,051 --> 00:46:20,633
and block meshing before you do some lighting,

982
00:46:20,813 --> 00:46:22,054
so that you have an idea of where

983
00:46:22,094 --> 00:46:23,095
the player's going to be going.

984
00:46:26,607 --> 00:46:29,269
And lastly, I want to end with this section,

985
00:46:29,409 --> 00:46:30,889
how to light a level.

986
00:46:31,770 --> 00:46:33,971
And I want to walk you through some steps

987
00:46:34,031 --> 00:46:36,712
that I would recommend you take with your own levels

988
00:46:36,993 --> 00:46:37,773
if you're starting out.

989
00:46:39,414 --> 00:46:41,455
This example will be in Unreal, but you can do it

990
00:46:41,515 --> 00:46:42,595
in any engine, basically.

991
00:46:43,816 --> 00:46:47,438
So first, you do your block out, or gray box,

992
00:46:47,498 --> 00:46:48,718
or whatever you want to call it.

993
00:46:49,063 --> 00:46:50,804
with just some basic real-time light.

994
00:46:51,185 --> 00:46:52,866
If you're doing some light baking,

995
00:46:52,926 --> 00:46:54,267
you don't want to do it at this stage

996
00:46:54,287 --> 00:46:56,028
because your level is constantly changing.

997
00:46:56,068 --> 00:46:57,269
You don't want to waste your time

998
00:46:57,789 --> 00:46:59,531
spending an hour lighting a room

999
00:46:59,631 --> 00:47:01,572
and then you end up deleting that room or something.

1000
00:47:01,592 --> 00:47:02,693
Then you've wasted your time.

1001
00:47:03,233 --> 00:47:04,915
So right here is when I recommend

1002
00:47:05,075 --> 00:47:06,656
you just use some basic real-time light

1003
00:47:06,676 --> 00:47:08,437
and not worry about the lighting so much.

1004
00:47:09,158 --> 00:47:10,979
For Unreal, I like switching it.

1005
00:47:11,039 --> 00:47:13,221
I like using stationary lights for this

1006
00:47:13,741 --> 00:47:15,523
and I also like enabling a setting

1007
00:47:15,543 --> 00:47:17,544
called Force No Precomputed Lighting.

1008
00:47:17,907 --> 00:47:21,629
which will help you not worry about light mapping and light

1009
00:47:21,669 --> 00:47:22,570
map baking and stuff.

1010
00:47:23,171 --> 00:47:25,712
And that's in the world settings in the Unreal Editor.

1011
00:47:26,133 --> 00:47:28,274
And in Unity, I like using real-time lights,

1012
00:47:28,655 --> 00:47:32,137
and I disable the auto-generate lighting checkbox

1013
00:47:32,457 --> 00:47:35,560
so that you're not constantly sitting and waiting and stopping

1014
00:47:35,960 --> 00:47:37,681
for the light maps to bake.

1015
00:47:39,122 --> 00:47:41,584
Although I hear the light map's faster now or something.

1016
00:47:41,684 --> 00:47:41,984
I don't know.

1017
00:47:42,004 --> 00:47:45,067
Bye.

1018
00:47:45,087 --> 00:47:45,487
Step two.

1019
00:47:46,449 --> 00:47:49,871
Now you want to set up your main mood, your big mood in your scene.

1020
00:47:50,652 --> 00:47:53,874
And to do that you want to set up your global lights.

1021
00:47:53,974 --> 00:47:55,915
So remember ambient and directional,

1022
00:47:56,115 --> 00:47:58,557
those apply to your whole entire game world.

1023
00:47:58,617 --> 00:48:00,659
So now's maybe the time to set that up

1024
00:48:00,719 --> 00:48:02,500
before you worry about smaller stuff.

1025
00:48:03,921 --> 00:48:06,183
And here you can see I have a bunch of sunlight

1026
00:48:06,363 --> 00:48:08,564
flooding in from those middle windows right here.

1027
00:48:08,584 --> 00:48:12,527
And I want to set up the main mood of this level

1028
00:48:12,787 --> 00:48:15,769
with like a big sunny sun-filled area.

1029
00:48:16,734 --> 00:48:21,997
And to do that, I need to set up the indirect light bounces,

1030
00:48:22,117 --> 00:48:24,019
especially for directional light or sunlight.

1031
00:48:24,659 --> 00:48:26,180
If you want something to feel like sunlight,

1032
00:48:26,200 --> 00:48:28,922
you should be paying attention to your indirect light bounce

1033
00:48:28,942 --> 00:48:29,302
settings.

1034
00:48:30,283 --> 00:48:32,424
And in Unity, that would be going to your light settings.

1035
00:48:32,665 --> 00:48:34,106
And in Unreal, that would involve

1036
00:48:34,126 --> 00:48:36,387
going to your world settings and adjust the light mass

1037
00:48:36,427 --> 00:48:37,588
section of the world settings.

1038
00:48:38,128 --> 00:48:41,571
And also look at the skylight actor in your Unreal scene.

1039
00:48:43,132 --> 00:48:43,792
And if you're not.

1040
00:48:44,210 --> 00:48:47,351
working with global illumination or light map baking for whatever reason,

1041
00:48:47,671 --> 00:48:52,712
then the next best thing is to hand place, like, invisible, faint point lights everywhere.

1042
00:48:54,052 --> 00:48:57,953
If you're, like, working on a game, like, I hear there's a rumor that

1043
00:48:58,053 --> 00:49:01,854
Fallout 4 did not have global illumination, so they had to place

1044
00:49:02,454 --> 00:49:07,915
faint point lights to, like, simulate and fake all the sunlight bouncing everywhere.

1045
00:49:08,656 --> 00:49:10,056
So you can totally do that as well.

1046
00:49:12,111 --> 00:49:14,514
In Unity, I like switching those lights to not important

1047
00:49:14,774 --> 00:49:16,656
so that they don't contribute to specular stuff.

1048
00:49:17,157 --> 00:49:19,599
And in Unreal, I like increasing the minimum roughness

1049
00:49:19,699 --> 00:49:21,821
on those lights so that they don't create

1050
00:49:21,862 --> 00:49:23,083
hot spots in your reflections.

1051
00:49:26,506 --> 00:49:29,209
Then step three, after you've kind of set up

1052
00:49:29,249 --> 00:49:30,791
the main mood of your scene, now you

1053
00:49:30,811 --> 00:49:33,294
should start thinking about the gameplay and lighting

1054
00:49:33,334 --> 00:49:34,195
for your critical path.

1055
00:49:35,030 --> 00:49:38,072
To review, the critical path is kind of like the ideal things

1056
00:49:38,172 --> 00:49:41,694
that your ideal player would kind of do in a certain order

1057
00:49:41,714 --> 00:49:42,755
or whatever in your level.

1058
00:49:44,015 --> 00:49:46,017
And at this stage, you should probably

1059
00:49:46,057 --> 00:49:48,458
focus on navigation and wayfinding.

1060
00:49:49,079 --> 00:49:52,601
Does the player know various entrances and exits

1061
00:49:52,701 --> 00:49:53,862
and know where they are?

1062
00:49:54,322 --> 00:49:56,643
David talked about this a lot in his talk,

1063
00:49:56,683 --> 00:49:58,545
about how they care a lot about wayfinding.

1064
00:49:58,845 --> 00:50:00,546
Lighting is another tool for you to do that.

1065
00:50:00,942 --> 00:50:09,448
And here I'm using it in like a really painfully obvious way where I'm using like bright orange lights on bright red doors.

1066
00:50:10,989 --> 00:50:18,734
Feel free to be more subtle than that in your own work, but for example, for the purposes of this example, it's like super obvious.

1067
00:50:20,535 --> 00:50:26,960
And when you're doing that, I also urge you to think about kind of like the hierarchy of different things you're doing here.

1068
00:50:27,554 --> 00:50:33,438
Here I would argue the left door is being lit to be more important than the door on the right.

1069
00:50:33,718 --> 00:50:37,340
The door on the left kind of has a wider spotlight and it's more intense and brighter

1070
00:50:37,640 --> 00:50:41,403
and also kind of has its own room and shadow so the contrast is much stronger.

1071
00:50:41,823 --> 00:50:46,145
Meanwhile that door on the right it's certainly an option and it certainly reads as like an

1072
00:50:46,245 --> 00:50:51,629
entrance or exit to this room but it's also a bit more faint so now we're emphasizing this

1073
00:50:51,669 --> 00:50:56,972
door on the left super important this door on the right it's like okay you know it's an okay door

1074
00:50:57,012 --> 00:50:57,192
but you

1075
00:50:57,625 --> 00:50:58,646
you know, that door on the left.

1076
00:50:59,007 --> 00:50:59,207
Yeah.

1077
00:51:02,229 --> 00:51:03,230
Then once you're done

1078
00:51:03,711 --> 00:51:05,292
doing main player wayfinding

1079
00:51:05,352 --> 00:51:07,634
and also you're like testing throughout all of this,

1080
00:51:07,714 --> 00:51:09,396
right, you should be

1081
00:51:09,496 --> 00:51:11,297
thinking about the other

1082
00:51:11,358 --> 00:51:13,299
interactions in your game. So if you're

1083
00:51:13,379 --> 00:51:15,501
setting up any NPCs or set pieces

1084
00:51:15,561 --> 00:51:17,043
or encounters, you should be

1085
00:51:17,363 --> 00:51:19,244
trying to light those encounters so that

1086
00:51:19,285 --> 00:51:21,166
the player will actually notice what's going on.

1087
00:51:22,087 --> 00:51:23,448
So here, these are like

1088
00:51:23,568 --> 00:51:25,030
critical gameplay objects.

1089
00:51:25,466 --> 00:51:28,769
that you might want to light enemies coming into the room,

1090
00:51:29,389 --> 00:51:32,652
or maybe the enemies are guarding an objective or something.

1091
00:51:32,912 --> 00:51:35,174
So on the left, they're guarding this orb.

1092
00:51:35,414 --> 00:51:37,916
The orb is very important in this game, I assure you.

1093
00:51:38,456 --> 00:51:41,178
And I have set up a blue,

1094
00:51:42,119 --> 00:51:43,640
blue-green kind of turquoise light.

1095
00:51:44,001 --> 00:51:46,623
And it's kind of coming at this perpendicular angle

1096
00:51:46,843 --> 00:51:48,124
to that orange arrow,

1097
00:51:48,204 --> 00:51:51,587
which is what I imagine as the player's critical path in this case.

1098
00:51:52,192 --> 00:51:54,072
And when you have that blue light coming

1099
00:51:54,232 --> 00:51:56,593
like a grazing perpendicular angle kind of,

1100
00:51:56,934 --> 00:51:58,814
that helps set that up as a rim light

1101
00:51:59,074 --> 00:52:01,856
to help emphasize the shapes going on there

1102
00:52:02,136 --> 00:52:03,576
instead of the surfaces.

1103
00:52:04,697 --> 00:52:06,858
Kind of the same thing going on in the example on the right.

1104
00:52:07,038 --> 00:52:09,099
You might see two small people,

1105
00:52:09,219 --> 00:52:11,460
two small silhouettes in the background.

1106
00:52:12,120 --> 00:52:14,221
And that's because I've kind of thrown

1107
00:52:14,261 --> 00:52:15,881
a background light behind them.

1108
00:52:16,422 --> 00:52:18,883
So those silhouettes end up popping out

1109
00:52:19,003 --> 00:52:20,703
and you notice them really easily.

1110
00:52:21,170 --> 00:52:24,431
So again, if you're lighting stuff where soldiers or enemies

1111
00:52:24,491 --> 00:52:25,851
jump through windows or something,

1112
00:52:26,051 --> 00:52:28,532
you might want to have a light behind them to help frame them

1113
00:52:28,692 --> 00:52:29,612
and help them pop out.

1114
00:52:33,913 --> 00:52:35,994
And when you're doing this, you should be thinking

1115
00:52:36,034 --> 00:52:37,234
about your texture paths.

1116
00:52:38,894 --> 00:52:41,255
Texturing is pretty important.

1117
00:52:41,615 --> 00:52:43,895
I think that's why David talks about using color a lot.

1118
00:52:43,915 --> 00:52:45,676
You should be thinking about the basic values.

1119
00:52:46,536 --> 00:52:49,117
This is a page I basically just said.

1120
00:52:49,500 --> 00:52:52,321
took these from some Unreal UDK documentation.

1121
00:52:52,401 --> 00:52:56,062
But here the albedo on the left is really dark,

1122
00:52:56,202 --> 00:52:58,723
and the albedo diffuse texture on the right is much brighter.

1123
00:52:59,263 --> 00:53:01,524
And when you have that dark albedo,

1124
00:53:01,764 --> 00:53:03,224
the light doesn't bounce as much,

1125
00:53:03,404 --> 00:53:05,705
because most game engines use the albedo texture

1126
00:53:05,725 --> 00:53:08,445
to calculate reflectance for indirect light.

1127
00:53:08,966 --> 00:53:11,866
So you can see that scene ends up feeling really, really dark

1128
00:53:11,906 --> 00:53:12,507
in a weird way.

1129
00:53:12,957 --> 00:53:16,139
But if you use a brighter albedo in that bottom right example,

1130
00:53:16,440 --> 00:53:18,581
now the scene is kind of evenly illuminated

1131
00:53:18,641 --> 00:53:20,203
and it feels much more like sunlight.

1132
00:53:20,783 --> 00:53:22,124
And one really easy way to check this

1133
00:53:22,184 --> 00:53:25,147
is if you open up your albedo or diffuse texture in Photoshop,

1134
00:53:25,467 --> 00:53:27,449
open up the levels histogram, look at that.

1135
00:53:27,749 --> 00:53:30,731
Most of your values should be more in the upper mid-range.

1136
00:53:31,112 --> 00:53:33,794
And you usually want to leave the left and right,

1137
00:53:33,834 --> 00:53:37,277
the extreme values, empty so that lighting can do its work.

1138
00:53:37,777 --> 00:53:40,119
So don't try to do extreme black or extreme white.

1139
00:53:41,801 --> 00:53:41,941
And.

1140
00:53:42,427 --> 00:53:43,347
Oh my god, I'm running out of time.

1141
00:53:43,447 --> 00:53:44,227
OK, I'll try to go fast.

1142
00:53:44,547 --> 00:53:48,408
So this is also where lighting is really, really important,

1143
00:53:48,488 --> 00:53:52,249
I think, where some stuff might be too dark

1144
00:53:52,529 --> 00:53:54,150
and some stuff might look great.

1145
00:53:54,770 --> 00:53:58,611
And I think that has a very strong political valence to it.

1146
00:53:59,351 --> 00:54:01,012
This is an example from an article called

1147
00:54:01,032 --> 00:54:03,492
Black Skin is Still a Radical Concept in Video Games.

1148
00:54:04,254 --> 00:54:09,816
And in this one, the woman on the right from Skyrim, I would argue, is lit pretty well.

1149
00:54:10,316 --> 00:54:13,357
You can read all the different contours and surface planes of her face.

1150
00:54:13,757 --> 00:54:18,838
Meanwhile, the woman on the left is lit very poorly, I think, where I can't really read

1151
00:54:18,898 --> 00:54:19,879
her face that well.

1152
00:54:20,459 --> 00:54:22,720
Her chin and jaw are totally lost.

1153
00:54:24,660 --> 00:54:29,101
And I'm not trying to call out Skyrim or Bethesda.

1154
00:54:30,821 --> 00:54:33,642
I don't think there was an evil racist at Bethesda going,

1155
00:54:33,682 --> 00:54:37,723
ha ha ha, right? I think this was just another example

1156
00:54:37,883 --> 00:54:41,244
of institutional racism that happens in video games where

1157
00:54:41,625 --> 00:54:45,686
maybe playtesters were testing mostly with white characters, so they never

1158
00:54:46,026 --> 00:54:49,307
saw that black characters are lit really poorly in this game

1159
00:54:50,107 --> 00:54:53,708
or need more specular contribution on their reflection or light probes

1160
00:54:53,768 --> 00:54:55,069
or whatever is going on in Skyrim.

1161
00:54:57,453 --> 00:54:59,814
It's important for us to take responsibility for our art.

1162
00:55:00,114 --> 00:55:02,955
And if in doubt, just ask a collaborator

1163
00:55:03,055 --> 00:55:05,236
so that you can avoid situations like these.

1164
00:55:08,117 --> 00:55:10,998
And then the last step is you should maybe

1165
00:55:11,118 --> 00:55:12,638
iterate on your level.

1166
00:55:12,818 --> 00:55:14,499
Keep trying different lighting schemes.

1167
00:55:15,462 --> 00:55:20,005
And this is an example of a sci-fi scene that's lit four different ways.

1168
00:55:20,105 --> 00:55:22,887
So keep experimenting with your lighting, but at the same time,

1169
00:55:23,167 --> 00:55:25,268
know when to stop and move on with your life.

1170
00:55:25,888 --> 00:55:28,730
This is a trap that a lot of level designers fall into.

1171
00:55:28,770 --> 00:55:31,412
They keep tweaking lights a little bit brighter, a little bit darker,

1172
00:55:31,652 --> 00:55:33,173
as if that'll make a huge difference.

1173
00:55:33,293 --> 00:55:33,933
It will not.

1174
00:55:34,393 --> 00:55:35,014
I guarantee you.

1175
00:55:35,054 --> 00:55:39,036
Just make the lights as good as you can, and then move on.

1176
00:55:39,056 --> 00:55:40,937
Maybe come back to it later if you have more time.

1177
00:55:41,117 --> 00:55:44,119
You won't have more time, but, you know, go back to it later.

1178
00:55:44,677 --> 00:55:48,219
just say that to yourself and move on and make the rest of your game.

1179
00:55:50,260 --> 00:55:51,200
So to review real quick,

1180
00:55:52,641 --> 00:55:56,663
lighting sets mood and evokes culture. There's four different light types common to a lot of

1181
00:55:56,863 --> 00:56:00,625
3D game engines and tool sets. Three-point lighting argues that you

1182
00:56:00,645 --> 00:56:04,868
should think about the task and function of each light and what it's doing for the image composition.

1183
00:56:05,908 --> 00:56:08,570
Light globally, do your big lights first and then

1184
00:56:09,070 --> 00:56:12,131
start doing spot checks for gameplay and critical path.

1185
00:56:12,792 --> 00:56:14,433
And also, know when to stop.

1186
00:56:14,940 --> 00:56:18,866
fiddling with your lights and move on and make your game and don't just keep

1187
00:56:19,107 --> 00:56:22,913
fiddling with one light. Thanks for listening. That was me.

1188
00:56:24,876 --> 00:56:25,598
Applaud. Bye.

